<TEXT>
fundamental changes in the educational system 
are needed to attract students to technical fields and assure that 
the nation has enough qualified scientists and engineers according 
to a study released today by the congressional office of technology 
assessment 
the ota a research arm of congress found in the study that 
though american schools have the capacity to produce the scientists 
and engineers needed by the nation many capable students never 
enter the fields because of a lack of money or preparation 
some experts the ota report said worry that a decline in 
collegeage students in the early 1990s and a lessened interest in 
the technical fields will cause a decline in the number of 
scientists and engineers 
despite these trends said the report shortages of scientists 
and engineers are not inevitable 
some adjustments will be made in the labor market the report 
said causing more students to go into science and engineering but 
the federal government may need to play a more active role 
the problem the report said could be attacked in two ways 
to correct shortterm shortages the government could encourage 
students to finish undergraduate and advanced degrees 
if the nation wants more scientists and engineers relatively 
quickly then retaining college and graduate students in science 
and engineering is the most useful policy strategy the report 
said it noted that currently only about 30 percent of graduates 
with bachelors degrees enter fulltime graduate level studies and 
only about half of doctoral candidates actually earn the doctoral 
degree 
those who leave unwillingly or prematurely are a rich resource 
that could be tapped the report said 
a longerterm solution is to expand and improve the talent pool 
of students willing and prepared to go into the science fields 
the years to do this are elementary school through the first 
years of college the report said increased recruitment into the 
technical fields might come through fullscale revision of 
elementary and secondary curricula tracking testing and course 
structure the report said though it noted that such a change 
will be hard to achieve given the scale of american education and 
the inertia of the existing system 
among the measures needed the report said are methods of 
recruiting more women and minorities into technical fields which 
traditionally have been dominated by white males 
the report said that developing a scientist or engineer requires 
20 years of schooling and a social and economic climate that 
encourages students to prepare themselves in the lower grades and 
to persist in college to the advanced degrees 
investing in future scientists and engineers is essential to the 
nation the report said 
although comprising only 4 percent of american workers 
scientists and engineers have specialized skills that are vital to 
the national welfare in developing new technology and in keeping 
the national industrial machine operating smoothly the report said 
the nation is well advised therefore the report said to 
seek an adequate supply of people prepared for science and 
engineering careers 
</TEXT>
