the prospects that the reagan administration 
will be able to meet its 1467 billion budget deficit goal for the 
fiscal year are growing dimmer 
the treasury department said tuesday that personal incometax 
collections picked up in may after the april revenue flow lagged 
but the cumulative deficit of 1275 billion for the first eight 
months of the 1988 fiscal year is still running 63 percent higher 
than last year 
if we continue the pace we have right now it will come in at 
about 159 billion said samuel d kahan chief financial 
economist of kleinwort benson government securities inc in chicago 
unless they do some funny accounting theyre not going to be 
able to hit their goal for the year or even the congressional 
budget offices projection of 157 billion he said 
the deficit last year totaled 1502 billion after soaring to a 
record 2211 billion in 1986 the target for the 1989 fiscal year 
beginning oct 1 is set at 136 billion by the grammrudman budget 
balancing law 
the persistent imbalance between what the government spends and 
what it takes in is blamed by economists for weakening the dollar 
encouraging a high trade deficit and pressuring interest rates 
upward 
in may the deficit totaled 225 billion about 5 billion less 
than expected by most analysts and down 369 percent from 356 
billion a year ago 
personal income tax collection was off by 258 percent in april 
513 billion against 718 billion a year earlier but may 
collections were nearly double those of last year they rose from 
93 billion in 1987 to 180 billion the treasury department said 
