<TEXT>
political action committees bankrolled by 
members of special interest groups are building up their war chests 
for the fall elections with the teamsters and realtors pacs each 
contributing close to 1 million to federal candidates so far 
five of the more than 4000 pacs registered with the federal 
election commission each had more than 2 million in cash on hand 
at the beginning of april an fec summary released tuesday showed 
together the registered pacs raised more than 213 million in 
the 15 months ending march 31 up 7 percent from the same period in 
1986 they had spent 162 million up 84 percent from spending at 
that point in the last election cycle the fec said 
labor unions and corporations are prohibited by law from giving 
money to federal campaigns so many set up pacs to which their 
employees and others can give money voluntarily politicians and 
interest groups also form pacs to promote their own interests 
the teamsters pac called democratic republican independent 
voter education committee raised the most during the 15month 
period 55 million followed by the american medical association 
pac at just under 4 million and the realtors political action 
committee at 37 million 
federal law allows pacs to give no more than 5000 to each 
candidate per election compared to the 1000 limit on 
contributions by individuals 
the teamsters and realtors pacs each reported giving close to 1 
million to federal candidates but the ama pac was 10th on the list 
of most contributions giving 585946 the summary said 
in cash on hand the teamster pac had the most 45 million 
followed by the international longshoremens association aflcio 
pac 27 million the national education association pac at 23 
million the auto dealers and drivers for free trade pac 23 
million and the realtors pac 21 million 
the pacs that raise the most do not necessarily give the most 
donations to candidates with money often going to a variety of 
fundraising and overhead costs 
the fec summary did not reflect any money the pacs might have 
spent on socalled independent expenditures such expenditures do 
not come under the 5000 limit as long as the money is spent to 
support or oppose a candidate but without coordination with the 
candidates campaign 
besides the teamsters ama and realtors pacs those that raised 
the most through march 31 followed by the sums they have 
contributed to candidates were 
