<TEXT>
the united states summit allies left toronto 
with much of what they wanted they won more debt relief for the 
worlds poorest countries and fought off an american attempt to 
eliminate agricultural subsidies 
from french president francois mitterrand to japanese prime 
minister noboru takeshita the allies expressed satisfaction with 
the outcome of the 14th annual economic summit of seven leading 
industrialized nations 
british prime minister margaret thatcher called the summit 
which wound up tuesday highly successful and takeshita said 
through a spokesman that he was finishing this summit meeting 
with a sense of fulfillment 
with the economies of the major industrialized nations on track 
the leaders turned their attention to the sticky question of 
agricultural subsidies and the desperate plight of the worlds 
poorest countries 
in advance of the summit mitterrand proposed that the leaders 
fashion a plan to ease the foreign debt burdens of the poorest of 
the poor countries those in vast subsaharan africa 
at the end of the meeting mitterrand said his suggestions were 
adopted in the leaders final communique 
so he told reporters im satisfied 
west german chancellor helmut kohl also praised the plan which 
offers a variety of options including slashing interest rates and 
forgiving some loans for easing the poor countries debt burden 
willy de clercq commissioner for external relations of the 
european community called the measure a big step forward the 
12nation trading bloc is represented at the summit 
the united states earlier this month backed off from its 
previous refusal to go along with concessions paving the way for 
the agreement 
japans finance minister kiichi miyazawa offered a sweeping 
proposal that would help such bigdebt countries as brazil and 
mexico the two latin american countries are the developing worlds 
largest debtors with a combined foreign debt of 220 billion the 
total for all the developing world is an estimated 1 trillion 
summiteers complained the japanese plan was so complicated and 
offered on such short notice that they did not have time to study 
it 
they renewed their support instead for the current 
casebycase approach drawn up in recent years to handle 
individually the money woes of the large debtors 
the japanese seem unfazed by the cool response to their plan 
which will no doubt be discussed at future international meetings 
takeshita was particularly pleased at the great deal of 
attention that was paid to the problems of developing countries 
according to michihiko kunihiro chief cabinet counselor for 
external affairs 
the europeans and the japanese tangled with the americans and 
canadians over what has become a bitterly disputed issue that of 
agricultural subsidies 
reagan has proposed as part of his freemarket philosophy that 
farm subsidies be scrapped by the year 2000 
american officials argue that european subsidies have made the 
european community a major agricultural supplier at a time of 
excess world capacity 
the europeans respond that they have begun the politically 
sensitive process of limiting european community subsidies to 
farmers but dont want to be pushed to meet a deadline 
the final statement offers vaguely worded language that called 
for a framework approach including short as well as longterm 
elements to promote reforms relieve strains in agricultural 
markets and which would be in line with goals concerning the 
reduction of all direct and indirect subsidies and other measures 
affecting agricultural trade 
de clercq expressed satisfaction with what he said was a 
compromise among the leaders 
agriculture is a bone of contention we succeeded in 
avoiding a row he told reporters 
the final wording he said underlines the reality the 
diversity of agriculture situations in the world a fact we had to 
take into account small family farms not large agribusinesses 
are common in europe 
kohl said the leaders were moving completely on a similar 
track 
the longterm goal must be a strong marketorientation of 
agriculture production he said for this realism and 
perspective are necessary 
canadian prime minister brian mulroney who had hoped for firm 
action to end the global subsidy war said it is not a perfect 
statement but it represents progress 
mrs thatcher who has fought in the european community for 
curbing the subsidies said there is a specific commitment to 
try first to freeze and then to roll back the subsidies and various 
other kinds of support for agriculture in an ordered and 
substantial way 
we have made a start she said 
