<TEXT>
rep john duncan who served 24 years in 
congress and was the ways and means committees ranking republican 
has died at age 69 after a long battle with cancer 
duncan died suddenly late tuesday at st marys medical center 
five days after being admitted for chemotherapy said mary sharp a 
hospital spokeswoman 
he had been listed in satisfactory condition up to tonight 
his condition deteriorated this evening she said 
family members were at his side when he died and were shocked by 
the death ms sharp said 
duncan who consistently won reelection by large margins had 
planned to run again to represent the 2nd district but duncan who 
suffered from cancer of the prostate and upper body announced may 
27 that he would not seek another term because of his poor health 
ever since my prostate cancer was discovered in 1980 i have 
considered the cancer just like any other illness duncan said in 
his announcement you hope and pray that it will go away so you 
can continue to work and enjoy life i truly wanted to run for a 
13th term 
he had kept in touch with other congress members who were 
battling cancer while continuing to work and said those 
relationships helped him as he struggled with the disease 
his 40yearold son john jimmy duncan jr stepped down as 
a knox county criminal court judge to run in augusts gop primary 
for the congressional seat 
duncan was considered a quiet lawmaker who concentrated on 
technical aspects of congressional matters often focusing on 
closing loopholes and polishing sloppy legislation 
during election years he sometimes came under fire by antipac 
groups for receiving large contributions from political action 
committees including those representing trial lawyers podiatrists 
and real estate agents 
duncan who was one of 10 children served in the army from 
194245 and received a law degree in 1948 
from then until 1956 he was an assistant state attorney general 
in 1959 he was elected mayor of knoxville serving until elected 
to congress in 1964 
he became the ranking republican on the ways and means committee 
after his 1984 reelection and was one of two republicans on the 
joint taxation committee 
funeral arrangements were not announced 
survivors include his wife lois and four children 
