<TEXT>
a bitterly divided supreme court today upheld 
by a 54 vote an oklahoma mans murder conviction and death 
sentence even though the presiding judge wrongly refused to exclude 
one juror 
the justices said bobby lynn ross conviction for killing an 
oklahoma policeman was not tainted because his lawyer used a 
peremptory challenge to oust the juror 
so long as the jury that sits is impartial the fact that the 
defendant had to use a peremptory challenge to achieve that result 
does not mean his constitutional right to a fair trial was 
violated chief justice william h rehnquist wrote for the court 
but justice thurgood marshall writing for the four dissenters 
said a mans life is at stake we should not be playing games 
in this case everyone concedes that the trial judge could not 
arbitrarily take away one of the defendants peremptory challenges 
yet that is in effect exactly what happened here 
the justices heard a first round of arguments in the oklahoma 
case last january a month before justice anthony m kennedy joined 
the court 
they scheduled a second round of arguments in april so kennedy 
could participate in the decision a move indicating that the 
eight justices had been evenly divided 
kennedys vote in which he joined the chief justices opinion 
indeed proved to control ross fate 
prosecutors said ross shot elk city okla police sgt steven 
mahan three times in the head after the officer arrived at a motel 
being robbed by ross on jan 5 1983 the murder weapon was found 
in ross pocket 
during jury selection at ross trial one potential juror said 
he would vote to impose the death penalty and would not consider 
a life sentence if ross were convicted 
ross lawyer attempted to have the person disqualified for 
cause but the trial judge refused the defense lawyer then used 
one of nine peremptory or automatic challenges to oust the 
potential juror 
ross contended that his right to a fair and impartial jury had 
been violated becaused the judges error forced the defense team to 
expend one peremptory challenge unnecessarily 
writing for the court today rehnquist said the trial judge 
clearly was wrong in not excluding the potential juror for cause 
but he said that error does not entitle ross to a new trial 
although we agree that the failure to remove the potential 
juror may have resulted in a jury panel different from that which 
would otherwise have decided the case we do not accept the 
argument that this possibility mandates reversal rehnquist said 
quoting from a previous high court ruling rehnquist said the 
constitution entitles a criminal defendant to a fair trial not a 
perfect one 
aside from kennedy rehnquist was joined by justices antonin 
scalia byron r white and sandra day oconnor 
marshall was joined in dissent by justices william j brennan 
harry a blackmun and john paul stevens 
the case is ross vs oklahoma 865309 
</TEXT>
