<TEXT>
two nuclear weapons were detonated 
simultaneously beneath the nevada desert this morning in a rare 
experiment carried out only a few times in 43 years of nuclear 
testing 
the test was conducted 40 miles from the town of mercury where 
33 soviet nuclear scientists are preparing for a historic series of 
joint nuclear experiments later this summer 
the devices were detonated at 7 am in a 750foot vertical 
shaft drilled in yucca flat about 85 miles northwest of las vegas 
energy department spokesman jim boyer said he felt very very 
slight motion at a control point 17 miles from ground zero 
the devices tested today he said were very very small and 
little ground motion could be expected away from the site 
in golden colo the national earthquake information center 
measured the magnitude of todays explosion at 31 on the richter 
scale spokesman waverly person a quake of magnitude 35 can cause 
slight damage 
the two devices were listed as having a combined force of less 
than 150 kilotons of tnt the exact size of each device was 
classified information boyer said 
the simultaneous test of two devices had been conducted only 
once in the past 20 years boyer has said adding that the 
experiment is a rarity 
energy department spokesman chris west said a check of doe 
records dating back to 1968 showed only one occasion september 
1982 when two devices were detonated simultaneously 
however there have been several occasions when two or more 
tests were conducted the same day 
soviet scientists are at the remote desert site to prepare for a 
blast in midaugust that will determine the ability of the kremlin 
and the united states to measure the size of each others nuclear 
tests 
the devices detonated today were the sixth and seventh tested 
this year at the nevada site six of the soviet scientists have 
been at the nevada site for three of those tests 
the united states has 34 technicians at the soviet test site 
preparing for a joint verification experiment in russia a month 
after the us test 
todays test brought to 682 the number of devices tested at the 
remote desert site since testing began in nevada in january 1951 
the first nuclear tests in the united states began in new mexico in 
1945 
</TEXT>
