<TEXT>
ancient ancestors of humans apparently ate soft 
fruits and leaves but their evolutionary cousins chomped on nuts 
and bark a new study of fossil teeth suggests 
the work bears on a longstanding debate over whether the two 
kinds of animals ate different diets or just differing amounts of 
the same food said researcher frederick grine 
the work is reported in thursdays issue of the british journal 
nature by grine associate professor of anthropology at the state 
university of new york at stony brook and richard kay professor 
of anatomy at duke university in durham nc 
they studied detailed replicas of molars that human ancestors 
called australopithecus left 25 million to 28 million years ago 
in south africa and that other beasts called paranthropus left 
there 15 million to 18 million years ago 
the two kinds of animals are also known as gracile and robust 
australopithecines respectively 
both walked upright but after their lineages split 25 million 
years ago the australopithecus group evolved toward modern humans 
while the paranthropus branch eventually died out 
grine and kay studied microscopic patterns of dental wear and 
compared them to teeth from modern animals with known diets 
paranthropus teeth showed more pits and wider pits and 
scratches suggesting a diet of tougher foods than australopithecus 
ate researchers said the difference probably led to the bigger 
teeth and larger jaws of paranthropus they said 
</TEXT>
