<TEXT>
the supreme court in a decision that could 
carry some impact for the continuing irancontra affair 
investigation today said grand jury targets may be forced to help 
prosecutors get at their accounts in foreign banks 
the court by an 81 vote ruled that prosecutors may compel the 
target of a grand jury investigation to provide written 
authorization so foreign banks will disclose records of the 
targets accounts there 
compelling such action does not violate the constitutionally 
protected privilege against selfincrimination because providing 
written authorization is not testimonial justice harry a blackmun 
wrote for the court 
the justices rejected arguments by a man identified in court 
documents only as john doe who is under investigation by a federal 
grand jury in texas the grand jury is looking into alleged 
fraudulent manipulation of oil cargos and receipt of unreported 
income 
the 5th us circuit court of appeals ruled in does case that 
he properly was held in contempt for refusing to authorize banks in 
the cayman islands and bermuda to provide his bank records to 
prosecutors 
todays decision upheld the 5th circuit courts ruling 
preserving the governments victory 
the ruling also could have a bearing on efforts to obtain 
foreign bank records in investigations of the irancontra affair 
the senate irancontra committee unsuccessfully sought a court 
order to compel retired air force maj gen richard secord to 
authorize the release of swiss bank records of corporations he 
headed 
the companies helped arrange the sale of us arms to iran and 
diversion of profits to nicaraguan rebels 
the senate is appealing a federal judges refusal to order 
secord to release the records 
also secords former business partner albert hakim is 
fighting an effort by independent counsel lawrence e walsh to 
subpoena records of swissbased corporations that hakim and secord 
ran that case is pending before a federal appeals court 
in todays decision blackmun said forcing doe to sign the 
authorization form does not amount to forcing him to testify 
against himself 
because the consent directive is not testimonial in nature we 
conclude that the district courts order compelling petitioner to 
sign the directive does not violate his fifth amendment privilege 
against selfincrimination blackmun said 
justice john paul stevens was the lone dissenter 
in a case dealing with a related issue the court said a 
custodian of subpoenaed corporate records may not withhold them 
from the government by claiming the act of providing the documents 
could incriminate the custodian 
by a 54 vote in a case from magnolia miss the justices said 
the subpoena must be honored even when a corporation is 
familyowned and the custodian of the records is the principle 
owner of the business 
chief justice william h rehnquist writing for the court said 
granting such custodians the right to withhold documents would 
jeopardize the governments fight against whitecollar crime he 
called that fight one of the most serious problems confronting 
law enforcement 
the court upheld a ruling that randy braswell head of worldwide 
machinery sales inc and worldwide purchasing inc must provide 
records the government sought in a tax investigation 
braswell is the sole officer of both corporations the only 
other corporate employee was his sisterinlaw who acted as his 
secretary 
braswells wife and mother also served nominally as directors of 
the corporations 
the internal revenue service in 1986 subpoenaed braswell to 
produce all corporate records for a federal grand jury he said the 
mere act of producing the records might tend to incriminate him in 
violation of his constitutional rights 
rehnquist was joined by blackmun stevens and justices byron r 
white and sandra day oconnor dissenting were justices anthony m 
kennedy william j brennan thurgood marshall and antonin scalia 
the case is braswell vs us 873 
the bank records case is doe vs us 861753 
