<TEXT>
here at a glance are highlights of actions 
taken wednesday by the supreme court 
 
pension benefits 
 
the court rescuing employers from having to pay potentially 
hundreds of millions of dollars in pension benefits limited the 
application of rulings requiring equal treatment of men and women 
in the workplace 
by a 54 vote the court said the state of florida does not have 
to pay 436 million to male state workers who retired since 1972 
the justices limited the retroactive impact of a 1978 high court 
ruling that barred employers from requiring women to make higher 
contributions to pension plans because on average they live longer 
than men and thus receive greater retirement benefits 
the case is florida vs long 861685 
 
foreign bank accounts 
 
the court said in a decision that could carry some impact for 
the continuing irancontra affair investigation that grand jury 
targets may be forced to help prosecutors get at their accounts in 
foreign banks 
the court by an 81 vote ruled that prosecutors may compel the 
target of a grand jury investigation to provide written 
authorization so foreign banks will disclose records of the 
targets accounts there 
the case is doe vs us 861753 
 
corporate records 
 
the court said a custodian of subpoenaed corporate records may 
not withhold them from the government by claiming the act of 
providing the documents could incriminate the custodian 
by a 54 vote in a case from magnolia miss the justices said 
the subpoena must be honored even when a corporation is 
familyowned and the custodian of the records is the principle 
owner of the business 
the case is braswell vs us 873 
 
texas death penalty 
 
the court upheld the way texas courts administer that states 
death penalty law dashing the hopes of more than 260 death row 
inmates 
the justices by a 63 vote ruled that convicted murderer and 
rapist donald gene franklin properly was sentenced to death for a 
1975 crime in san antonio 
the case is franklin vs lymaugh 875546 
 
murder conviction 
 
the court upheld by a 54 vote an oklahoma mans murder 
conviction and death sentence even though the presiding judge 
wrongly refused to exclude one juror 
the justices said bobby lynn ross conviction for killing an 
oklahoma city policeman was not tainted because his lawyer used a 
peremptory challenge to oust the juror 
the case is ross vs oklahoma 865309 
 
prosecutors misconduct 
 
the court ruled that federal judges may not throw out 
indictments because of misconduct by prosecutors unless the 
defendants can show they would not have been indicted were it not 
for such misconduct 
the 81 ruling upheld the reinstatment of an indictment in a 
denver case against the bank of nova scotia and others accused of 
setting up and taking part in phony tax shelters 
the case is bank of nova scotia vs us 87578 
 
civil rights 
 
the court made it easier for people to sue in state court those 
public officials they accuse of violating federal civil rights laws 
the justices by a 72 vote reinstated a milwaukee mans 23 
million lawsuit against 10 city policemen the suit contends that 
the white officers used excessive force and falsely arrested bobby 
felder because he is black 
the case is felder vs casey 87526 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

