president leslie manigat and called on the new military government 
in haiti to respect human rights 
charles e redman assistant secretary of state for public 
affairs reacted to confirmation by haitian authorities that an 
unspecified number of prisoners have been held since mondays 
military coup by lt gen henry namphy 
we find that alarming as one of the first acts of the namphy 
regime redman said of the arrests we have taken that issue up 
with haitian officials making clear that we expect strict 
respect forinternationally recognized human and civil rights 
us diplomats in haiti who have not had contact with namphy 
since the takeover voiced their concern over the arrests to lower 
level officials redman said 
meanwhile the reagan administration will continue a 36 million 
humanitarian aid program and try diplomacy to nudge the caribbean 
nations new military government toward democracy 
there is no break in the diplomatic relations were not 
contemplating it state department spokeswoman phyllis oakley 
said tuesday 
once again she denounced the coup as a setback for democracy 
but she and other state department officials some of whom spoke 
on condition of anonymity made clear that the united states would 
work with the new military regime 
i think there are examples of many governments around the 
world of whom we dont particularly approve with whom we have 
relations and have dealings she said 
were talking about the situation as it evolves in haiti 
were continuing the operation of our embassy there the 
spokeswoman said 
she said there are no plans to halt us humanitarian 
assistance which is distributed directly to haitians by 
nongovernmental agencies including many based in the united 
states this fiscal years plan calls for 30 million for 
development and relief programs and 6 million in the form of 
surplus american food 
a us diplomat said there was no thought of interrupting 
this assistance who would it hurt if we stopped the aid the poor 
people of haiti not the leaders 
economic sanctions also have been ruled out the diplomat said 
such sanctions would hurt the estimated 40000 haitians who have 
jobs assembling products for american markets these 40000 people 
in turn each support an average of five other people he said 
haiti has the lowest per capita income in the western hemisphere 
about 60 million in direct us assistance to the haitian 
government was suspended last november and will remain frozen 
the reaction to events in haiti are in stark contrast to what 
the united states did in an analogous case the removal of 
panamanian president eric delvalle by military chief manuel antonio 
noriega earlier this year 
that sparked swift action by the reagan administration which 
continued to recognize delvalle as the legitimate leader of the 
country and imposed massive economic sanctions on panama in an 
effort to drive noriega from office the effort has failed 
a state department official said that before acting in the 
noriega case the administration took into account the longstanding 
relationship between the united states and panama and we saw a 
significant element of dissatisfaction among the people of panama 
that we thought could be translated into his noriegas downfall 
the united states appears to have less influence among the 
people of haiti which had been a virtual hemispheric outcast for 
decades under the dictatorship of francois duvalier and his son 
jean claude duvalier who fled the country in february 1986 
haiti is so poor economically and inexperienced in the formation 
of democratic institutions that tough measures would have little 
impact the official said 
namphy is immune to certain kinds of pressure because he 
doesnt have much to lose the official said haiti is already 
at the bottom 
the official also noted there has been little pressure on 
capitol hill for tough measures against the new haitian regime 
while in the case of panama many members of congress called for 
stern action 
