<TEXT>
driver and passengerside air bags will be 
standard equipment on 1989 lincoln continentals ford motor co 
announced wednesday in a move that safety advocates said will 
trigger adoption of the restraint system throughout the auto 
industry 
this is the final event that will make the air bag inevitable 
as a standard safety feature in american automobiles ralph nader 
said following fords announcement 
fords plan will make it the first us automaker to offer air 
bags as standard equipment on both sides of the front seat west 
germanys porsche since 1987 has offered twin air bags as standard 
equipment on some models 
helen petrauskas ford vice president for environmental and 
safety engineering told reporters that safety has become a quality 
that sells among car buyers 
the safety race is in high gear she said oldfashioned 
word of mouth about safety features will provide the biggest 
spark for selling safety 
the continentals airbag system will have four sensors on the 
front of the car to trigger the air bags in the event of a frontal 
crash equivalent to a 25 mph collision with a parked car said 
robert munson director of the ford automotive safety office 
the system is designed to be used with seat belts not to 
replace them 
the air bags inflate with nitrogen gas in 125th of a second and 
deflate immediately design of the passengerside air bag was 
difficult technically because the bag must cover both the window 
and center positions of the front seat and also must travel a 
greater distance on inflating ford said 
the company had no firm estimate of how much the air bags would 
add to the cost of the continental ford said each bag would cost 
the company 300 to 350 
ford in 1985 made driverside air bags standard equipment on its 
tempo and topaz models the automakers 1990 line will have 11 
models with standard driverside air bags with projected sales of 
1 million petrauskas said 
the company last year successfully opposed a federal regulation 
to require air bags on both sides of cars not equipped with 
automatic seat belts petrauskas said the delay in the requirement 
allowed the company to install driverside bags without waiting for 
development of passengerside bags 
besides ford chrysler corp has adopted air bags for some 
models the company in may said driverside air bags would be 
standard equipment on six models built this year and by 1990 on 
all models built in the united states 
general motors corp the nations largest automaker in 1988 
offered driverside air bags as an option on one model the number 
will be expanded to five in 1989 and the next year 500000 gmmade 
cars will have driverside air bags as standard equipment gm 
spokesman don postma said in detroit 
the center for auto safety a consumers group that monitors the 
auto industry said only honda among the japanese automakers offers 
an air bag as standard equipment on any model 
nader criticized other automakers for not keeping up with ford 
and chrysler in safety features 
it is not nice to see gm and the japanese automakers lagging 
behind nader said theyre jeopardizing their customers 
lives 
