<TEXT>
a house panel on wednesday approved a 400 
millionayear aids testing and counseling bill that includes stiff 
penalties for breaching the confidentiality of a patients test 
results 
the bill in the works for a year before the house energy and 
commerce committee would give grants to states and to clinics 
health centers and hospitals to expand testing programs it would 
require posttest counseling to all who take the test for the fatal 
disease whether they were infected or not 
the committee sent the bill to the house floor on a voice vote 
after sponsors took out a section banning discrimination against 
people with aids or the virus that causes it 
the broad privatesector nondiscrimination policy was 
clearly too controversial for the current political climate said 
rep henry waxman dcalif chairman of the committees health 
panel 
rep ron wyden dore called the omission a terrible public 
health mistake he said those most likely to have and transmit 
aids would be reluctant to come in for tests if they could lose 
their jobs insurance or housing on the basis of the results 
the presidents commission on aids recently recommended a 
federal policy banning discrimination against victims of acquired 
immune deficiency syndrome wyden said he would use the 
recommendation in an attempt to build bipartisan support for 
restoring the provision on the house floor 
however waxman said he was pessimistic about the chances of 
winning back the ban on discrimination unless president reagan 
specifically backs the panels recommendation 
we need the president not the presidents commission he 
said without it reagans support i cant see that members are 
going to be willing to vote for it have the courage to vote for 
it in an election year 
waxman also said elimination of the discrimination portion 
removes the biggest objection that some of the rightwingers 
have and makes it much less likely that the bill would be blocked 
in the senate where it is pending in a committee 
in work sessions tuesday and wednesday the committee rejected a 
long series of amendments sponsored by rep william dannemeyer 
rcalif most of them proposals that had failed earlier in 
waxmans subcommittee 
among them were attempts to require testing of all prisoners 
marriage license applicants and hospital admittees the bill does 
require that states test people convicted of prostitution sexual 
assault or crimes related to intravenous drug abuse in order to 
qualify for federal testing and counseling money 
dannemeyer also failed to win approval of a requirement that 
people with aids or the aids virus be reported to authorities by 
name the bill requires that cases be reported with statistical and 
demographic information but does not require identifying 
information 
other unsuccessful dannemeyer amendments would have reduced from 
10000 to 2000 the maximum fine for intentional or negligent 
violation of confidentiality required states to outlaw gay 
bathhouses in order to receive money and required doctors to 
notify spouses sex partners or iv needle partners if the patient 
didnt notify them within a reasonable period 
the last was rejected after members of both parties said the 
bill already exempts doctors from confidentiality requirements in 
such situations they said a notification requirement would 
constitute a tremendous burden and make doctors vulnerable to 
malpractice suits 
aids renders the bodys immune system incapable of resisting 
other diseases and infections the virus most often is spread 
through close contact with blood blood products or semen from 
infected persons its chief victims have been homosexual men and 
intravenous drug users 
