senate supporters of a bill imposing harsh new 
sanctions against whitedominated south africa acknowleged 
wednesday they do not have the votes to override a certain veto by 
president reagan 
but they said that in order to highlight opposition to south 
africas racial policies they would battle for senate passage of 
the bill which requires an end to most trade with south africa as 
well as the withdrawal of all us corporate investment 
testifying before the senate foreign relations committee deputy 
secretary of state john c whitehead strongly opposed the harsh 
sanctions measure as counterproductive 
and sen jesse helms rnc the leading opponent of using 
sanctions to increase pressures on south africa to adopt majority 
rule reforms said he will introduce legislation repealing the less 
severe sanctions bill passed over president reagans veto two years 
ago 
whitehead said that while the reagan administration believes 
apartheid is repugnant sanctions are the wrong tool because 
south africa has the resources to resist an economic siege and has 
been preparing for such a contingency for many years 
he said it has become clear over the past two years that the 
industrial allies of the united states will resist the us lead 
and will not impose sanctions of their own 
he said south africa could at will cut off exports of strategic 
minerals vital to us industrial efforts 
americans must accept the fact that us leverage in south 
africa is limited whitehead said 
resorting to drastic remedies such as the misuse of american 
power to destabilize the south african economy only increases the 
chances of a catastrophic outcome for all south africans 
whitehead said 
instead he said our mission should beone of using all 
available means to maximize our influence and leverage 
