<TEXT>
the coast guard set limits wednesday on 
the number of barges towboats can work on the droughtshoaled 
mississippi river while a growing backlog of hundreds of delayed 
barges accumulated at memphis 
the new rules which apply from caruthersville mo to 
greenville miss are the first such restrictions set for a major 
portion of the mississippi though temporary barge limits have been 
imposed for small areas said coast guard cmdr michael donohoe 
with the new limits southbound towboats must have no more than 
20 barges while northbound boats will be limited to 25 only 16 of 
which can be loaded barges can draw a maximum of 85 feet of water 
mississippi river workboats which are called towboats even 
though they push their loads generally can handle 40 or more 
barges each industry officials say they lose 4000 to 10000 in 
income for each barge left behind 
the limits were sought by barge company representatives and are 
aimed at preventing towboats operators from running their loads 
aground in the shrunken mississippi donohoe said 
a continuing lack of rain throughout the mississippi river 
region has dropped the river to more than 20 feet lower at memphis 
than it was last june and most towboat operators already have cut 
their loads to 20 barges 
donohoe said industry officials worry that some boat captains 
might take on more than they can safely handle in the low water 
were got to make sure that somebody doesnt get out there and 
mess it up for everybody he said 
the barge limits will apply as long as the low water persists 
donohoe said and could be tightened further if the river continues 
to drop 
the barge limits were set as towboats with more than 600 barges 
lined up on the river near memphis the mississippi has been closed 
six miles above the city while the lenel bean a 240foot dredge 
scoops out a 1500footlong buildup of sand on the river bottom 
authorities said the dredging would take until friday afternoon 
and more than 1200 barges many of them recently freed from 
similar backlogs to the north and south were expected to stack up 
in the memphis area 
brig gen thomas sands president of the mississippi river 
commission said the army corps of engineers has located more than 
30 spots on the lower mississippi that will likely need dredging 
this summer 
sands said the river will remain open to commercial traffic 
throughout the summer even though dredging will cause temporary 
barge backups from time to time 
sands said controlled runoff from reservoirs on the missouri 
river and other rivers feeding the mississippi will keep it open 
mississippi tributaries are low too however and sands said a 
continuing lack of rain could at some point shut down commercial 
traffic on the river but he said that was unlikely 
theres got to be a doomsday point out there somewhere right 
now i dont know anybody that ive talked to who can give me any 
idea where that is right now we are not on the brink of 
disaster he said 
the river measured 86 feet below zero on the memphis river 
gauge wednesday zero on the gauge was set in the 1800s at 18391 
feet above sea level and the river measured more than 12 feet 
above zero last year this time 
the record low before the latest drop was set in 1981 at 73 
feet below zero and the corps of engineers said the reading could 
be more than nine feet below zero by next week 
