<TEXT>
amnesty international in a report for publication 
thursday urged the israeli government to investigate reports that 
army misuse of tear gas in quelling palestinian unrest has caused 
the deaths of men women and babies 
the londonbased human rights group said it was concerned the 
gas although made for use in the open air has been thrown into 
houses clinics schools hospitals and mosques during the 
sixmonthold uprising in the occupied west bank and gaza strip 
the gas has frequently been used in high concentrations in 
residential areas where it can drift into peoples homes the 
report said 
amnesty international cited seven cases in which palestinians 
ranging from five days to 57 years old died as a result of inhaling 
tear gas and said local doctors had reported more than 40 such 
deaths 
it said the usmade cs and cn gases carried strict 
instructions against their use in enclosed areas and noted that 
the united states last month announced it was halting their export 
to israel because of reports of their misuse 
eviatar manor an israeli embassy spokesman in london said 
amnesty international reports are always studied carefully by the 
israeli authorities and once this report arrives in israel it will 
be given the usual serious study and an authoritative reply will be 
forwarded to amnesty international 
the organization cited reports from various sources that israeli 
soldiers were using tear gas not only for riot control but also 
in such a way as to constitute a punitive measure to harass and 
intimidate palestinian residents 
the gas has sometimes been used at night as a punitive measure 
against residents of villages or refugee camps who had clashed 
earlier in the day with israeli army soldiers it said 
it has been used when israeli soldiers have been pursuing 
demonstrators often when they have taken refuge in hospitals or 
near peoples homes there has been at least one case in which an 
individual was deliberately shut in a room which was then sprayed 
with tear gas the report said 
amnesty international expressed concern that israeli authorities 
made no public statement condemning the use of tear gas in confined 
spaces and that the israeli army appeared to have made very few 
investigations to ascertain whether there is any truth in the 
allegations 
it also accused the israelis of failing to inform hospitals of 
the gases contents and of ways to treat victims 
</TEXT>
