<DOCNO> AP880622-0292 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
in the fastpaced hightech world of the 1990s 
companies thinking about name changes may be better off sticking 
with something old and familiar 
thats one bit of advice from landor associates a san 
franciscobased consulting firm that recently completed a survey of 
consumer perceptions of the names of some of the nations biggest 
corporations 
landor asked 1000 consumers in shopping malls in 12 cities to 
rate 672 different names in terms of familiarity and esteem 
sara lee ranked in the top 15 percent in the latest survey that 
was a marked improvement from the days when it was known as 
consolidated foods and ranked in the bottom 10 percent of the 
landor sample 
allegheny airlines once ranked in the bottom 20 percent in the 
landor survey but placed in the top 40 percent after changing its 
name to usair 
in the 90s major corporations will rediscover the raw image 
power of their established names and may find it much more 
efficient to modify or add meaning to them rather than start from 
scratch said john diefenbach president of the image management 
and strategic design consulting firm 
the survey said consumers thought none too highly of some of the 
hightech names such as usx primerica and unisys 
the old names of those corporations us steel american can 
and the premerger burroughs and sperry respectively each had 
placed higher in previous surveys 
the recently abandoned name allegis as another example ranked 
in the bottom 5 percent of the latest landor survey but the name 
of allegis biggest subsidiary united airlines placed in the top 
15 percent 
shareholders recently dumped the allegis name and returned to 
ual corp as the parent company previously was known 
the message is very simple diefenbach said meaningless 
names and symbols can confuse and alienate the consumer 
so how can companies avoid similar pitfalls 
diefenbach says when new names are considered companies need to 
remember the longstanding equity built up in longstanding brand 
images 
when new names are required he recommends they provide 
genuine favorable and recognizable meaning to the consumer 
otherwise illconceived name changes can destroy good will 
and obscure consumer recognition diefenbach said 
</TEXT>
