<TEXT>
parliament has passed a law that makes scotch 
a protected trademark 
under the measure no whisky can be called scotch unless it 
conforms to standards set by the scotch whisky association matured 
for at least three years in oak casks with charred insides and 
using only scottish ingredients like highland water 
the law passed the house of lords on tuesday and now awaits the 
formality of the queens signature said bill walker a scottish 
lawmaker for the ruling conservative party and sponsor of the bill 
the new law would empower whisky distillers to prosecute anyone 
violating scotch standards walker said wednesday he said it was 
modeled on a law that prevents drinks being called champagne unless 
they come from the province of champagne in france and conform to 
its standards 
walker said more than 90 percent of scotch is exported and 
earns scotland 18 billion a year 
