<TEXT>
brazil on wednesday reached agreement on 
a 58 billion refinancing of its foreign private debt the largest 
in the third world but said the pact did not formally end its 
moratorium on interest payments 
the accord with the nations private bankers the first major 
agreement since the moratorium was invoked in february 1987 
includes 52 billion in new loans 
after eight months of long and difficult negotiations brazil 
concluded one of the best refinancing accords ever reached by a 
debtor nation finance minister mailson da nobrega said at a news 
conference 
he said the accord which was simultaneously announced in new 
york did not formally revoke brazils foreign debt payment 
moratorium 
da nobrega said it is possible the moratorium would end 
formally once brazils 700 creditor banks agreed to wednesdays 
refinancing plan which was closed in new york with the committee 
of 14 banks representing all the countrys private creditors 
the accord is not a solution to the countrys foreign debt 
problems da nobrega said but it removes the biggest obstacle 
in our relations with the international financial community and 
eliminates uncertainties over the national economy 
the agreement covers interest due in 1987 1988 and the first 
half of 1989 it gives brazil 52 billion in new money to be paid 
back over a 20 years with an eightyear grace period 
that money will go toward paying the interest on the longterm 
debt with private banks which is 636 billion 
brazil owes a total of 121 billion to private bankers and 
government institutions 
the accord also gives brazil an additional 600 million in 
shortterm credit lines towards the financing of exports and 
imports 
da nobrega said the accord eliminates links with the 
international monetary fund a politically sensitive issue 
however a 600 million payment is dependent on brazil meeting imf 
economic guidelines currently being worked out with the fund in a 
separate agreement 
brazil is the first country to sign a mediumterm accord 
without having to have any rigid links with the fund said the 
finance minister 
he said brazil would make a 345 million payment on its march 
private debt interest on friday through the end of june brazil 
will then pay 1 billion in interest due in april and may 
the agreements interest rate spread the extra interest 
charged to highrisk clients above international interest rates 
of 08125 percent is one of the lowest worldwide da nobrega said 
in addition da nobrega said banks holding brazilian debt would 
be able to swap it for investments in local enterprises this 
applies mainly to smaller banks and will go into effect one year 
after the 700 creditor banks approve the accord 
banks have three years to make the transfer of debt for 
investments at a maximum rate of 50 million monthly and with a 
limit of 18 billion 
da nobrega said the accord allows brazil to pull out of the 
agreement if there are any external economic shocks that impair 
brazils ability to meet interest payments he said this could 
apply to even a drop in brazils trade surplus which has been 
averaging more than 1 billion monthly 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

